ringworth, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Grene","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Irish, English:  see  Green  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Green","meanings":["English: either a nickname for someone who was fond of dressing in this color (Old English <i>grēne</i>) or was young or immature, or who had played the part of the ‘Green Man’ in the May Day celebrations, or a topographic name for someone who lived near a village green (Middle English <i>grene</i>, a transferred use of the color term). This is one of the most common and widespread of English surnames. In North America it has assimilated cognates from other languages, notably German <b>Grün</b> (see   Gruen  ) and Dutch   Groen  ; compare 7 below. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","English: alternatively, from a Middle English personal name <i>Grene</i>.","Irish: adopted for <b>Ó hUainín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Uainín</i>’, a personal name from a pet form of <i>uaine</i> ‘green’, see   Honan  ."]}]},{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["‘Morning dew’; also ‘generosity’."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":41,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Agnes de Grene was born in 1341, in Boughton, Northamptonshire, England. She had at least 1 daughter with William la Zouche 3rd Baron Zouche. She died in 1391, in Harringworth, Northamptonshire, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1341–1391":"1341–1391","1341–1396":"1341–1396","1330–1427":"1330–1427","1341":"1341","1330":"1330","1396":"1396","1382":"1382","1391":"1391","1427":"1427","Boughton, Northamptonshire, England":"Boughton, Northamptonshire, England","Harringworth, Northamptonshire, England":"Harringworth, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1341–1391":"1341–1391","1341–1396":"1341–1396","1330–1427":"1330–1427","1341":"1341","1330":"1330","1396":"1396","1382":"1382","1391":"1391","1427":"1427","Boughton, Northamptonshire, England":"Boughton, Northamptonshire, England","Harringworth, Northamptonshire, England":"Harringworth, Northamptonshire, England"},"fr":{"1341–1391":"1341–1391","1341–1396":"1341–1396","1330–1427":"1330–1427","1341":"1341","1330":"1330","1396":"1396","1382":"1382","1391":"1391","1427":"1427","Boughton, Northamptonshire, England":"Boughton, Northamptonshire, Angleterre","Harringworth, Northamptonshire, England":"Harringworth, Northamptonshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lady Agnes de Grene est née en 1341, à Boughton, Northamptonshire, Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec William la Zouche 3rd Baron Zouche. Elle est décédée en 1391, à Harringworth, Northamptonshire, Angleterre, à l’âge de 50 ans."},"de":{"1341–1391":"1341–1391","1341–1396":"1341–1396","1330–1427":"1330–1427","1341":"1341","1330":"1330","1396":"1396","1382":"1382","1391":"1391","1427":"1427","Boughton, Northamptonshire, England":"Boughton, Northamptonshire, England","Harringworth, Northamptonshire, England":"Harringworth, Northamptonshire, England","lifeSummary":"Lady Agnes de Grene wurde 1341 in Boughton, Northamptonshire, England geboren. Sie hatte mit William la Zouche 3rd Baron Zouche mindestens 1 Tochter. Sie starb 1391 im Alter von 50 Jahren in Harringworth, Northamptonshire, England."},"ht":{"1341–1391":"1341–1391","1341–1396":"1341–1396","1330–1427":"1330–1427","1341":"1341","1330":"1330","1396":"1396","1382":"1382","1391":"1391","1427":"1427","Boughton, Northamptonshire, England":"Boughton, Northamptonshire, England","Harringworth, Northamptonshire, England":"Harringworth, Northamptonshire, England"},"hu":{"1341–1391":"1341–1391","1341–1396":"1341–1396","1330–1427":"1330–1427","1341":"1341","1330":"1330","1396":"1396","1382":"1382","1391":"1391","1427":"1427","Boughton, Northamptonshire, England":"Boughton, Northamptonshire, England","Harringworth, Northamptonshire, England":"Harringworth, Northamptonshire, England"},"id":{"1341–1391":"1341–1391","1341–1396":"1341–1396","1330–1427":"1330–1427","1341":"1